You said:
Write a function that takes a city name as input and fetches the current weather data from Open-Meteo
ChatGPT said:

Here's a Python function that takes a city name as input, gets the geographic coordinates using the Open-Meteo Geocoding API, and then fetches the current weather using the Open-Meteo Weather API.

You'll need the requests library to make HTTP requests:

python
import requests

def get_current_weather(city_name):
    try:
        # Step 1: Get coordinates using Open-Meteo Geocoding API
        geocode_url = "https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search"
        geocode_params = {"name": city_name, "count": 1, "language": "en", "format": "json"}
        geo_response = requests.get(geocode_url, params=geocode_params)
        geo_data = geo_response.json()

        if "results" not in geo_data or not geo_data["results"]:
            return f"City '{city_name}' not found."

        location = geo_data["results"][0]
        latitude = location["latitude"]
        longitude = location["longitude"]

        # Step 2: Get current weather using Open-Meteo Weather API
        weather_url = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast"
        weather_params = {
            "latitude": latitude,
            "longitude": longitude,
            "current_weather": "true"
        }
        weather_response = requests.get(weather_url, params=weather_params)
        weather_data = weather_response.json()

        if "current_weather" in weather_data:
            weather = weather_data["current_weather"]
            return {
                "city": location["name"],
                "temperature": weather["temperature"],
                "windspeed": weather["windspeed"],
                "winddirection": weather["winddirection"],
                "weathercode": weather["weathercode"],
                "time": weather["time"]
            }
        else:
            return "Weather data not available."
    except Exception as e:
        return f"An error occurred: {e}"

# Example usage
print(get_current_weather("Berlin"))

Notes:

  • This function uses Open-Meteo’s free APIs.

  • Weather codes can be interpreted using Open-Meteo's documentation if needed.

  • No API key is required for these endpoints.

  • You can further enhance it by handling multiple results from the geocoding API or by formatting the output nicely.

You said:
Write a function that takes a city name as input and fetches the current weather data from Open-Meteo
ChatGPT said:

Sure! Below is a complete Python function that takes a city name as input and fetches the current weather data from Open-Meteo's API:

✅ Python Code

python
import requests

def get_current_weather(city_name):
    """
    Fetch current weather data for a given city using Open-Meteo APIs.
    
    Args:
        city_name (str): Name of the city
    
    Returns:
        dict or str: Weather data dictionary or error message
    """
    try:
        # Step 1: Get latitude and longitude from Open-Meteo Geocoding API
        geocode_url = "https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search"
        geocode_params = {"name": city_name, "count": 1, "language": "en", "format": "json"}
        geo_response = requests.get(geocode_url, params=geocode_params)
        geo_data = geo_response.json()

        if "results" not in geo_data or not geo_data["results"]:
            return f"City '{city_name}' not found."

        location = geo_data["results"][0]
        latitude = location["latitude"]
        longitude = location["longitude"]

        # Step 2: Get current weather using Open-Meteo Weather API
        weather_url = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast"
        weather_params = {
            "latitude": latitude,
            "longitude": longitude,
            "current_weather": True
        }
        weather_response = requests.get(weather_url, params=weather_params)
        weather_data = weather_response.json()

        if "current_weather" not in weather_data:
            return "Weather data not available."

        current = weather_data["current_weather"]
        return {
            "City": location["name"],
            "Country": location.get("country", "Unknown"),
            "Temperature (°C)": current["temperature"],
            "Wind Speed (km/h)": current["windspeed"],
            "Wind Direction (°)": current["winddirection"],
            "Time": current["time"]
        }

    except Exception as e:
        return f"An error occurred: {e}"

# Example usage
if __name__ == "__main__":
    city = input("Enter a city name: ")
    weather = get_current_weather(city)
    print(weather)

🔧 What You Need

  • Python 3

  • requests library: Install with

    bash
    pip install requests

You said:
i have to paste the link inside the HTML code before </body>
ChatGPT said:

Great question! You're close — but when linking a CSS file in your HTML, you should put the <link> tag inside the <head> section, not before </body>.

✅ Correct Placement:

Put this line inside the <head> tag of your HTML:

html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

✅ Example HTML Template:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>My Web Page</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css"> <!-- ✅ CSS goes here -->
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Hello, world!</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph.</p>

</body>
</html>

❌ What not to do:

Do not place it before </body> like this:

html
<!-- ❌ Wrong place -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</body>

That will still technically work in some browsers, but it’s not recommended because:

  • Styles may load after the page appears.

  • It breaks the convention and causes layout flashes.

import requests

def get_current_weather(city_name):
    # Step 1: Get latitude and longitude using geocoding
    geocode_url = "https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search"
    geocode_params = {"name": city_name, "count": 1, "language": "en", "format": "json"}
    geo_response = requests.get(geocode_url, params=geocode_params)
    geo_data = geo_response.json()

    if "results" not in geo_data or not geo_data["results"]:
        return f"❌ City '{city_name}' not found."

    # Extract latitude and longitude
    location = geo_data["results"][0]
    latitude = location["latitude"]
    longitude = location["longitude"]

    # Step 2: Use lat/lon to get weather
    weather_url = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast"
    weather_params = {
        "latitude": latitude,
        "longitude": longitude,
        "current_weather": True
    }
    weather_response = requests.get(weather_url, params=weather_params)
    weather_data = weather_response.json()

    if "current_weather" not in weather_data:
        return "❌ Weather data not available."

    # Return weather info
    current = weather_data["current_weather"]
    return {
        "City": location["name"],
        "Country": location.get("country", "Unknown"),
        "Temperature (°C)": current["temperature"],
        "Wind Speed (km/h)": current["windspeed"],
        "Time": current["time"]
    }

# 🏃‍♀️ Run the function
if __name__ == "__main__":
    city = input("🌆 Enter a city name: ")
    weather = get_current_weather(city)
    print("🌦️ Weather info:", weather)

    geocode_url = "https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search"
    geocode_params = {"name": city_name, "count": 1, "language": "en", "format": "json"}
    geo_response = requests.get(geocode_url, params=geocode_params)
    geo_data = geo_response.json()

    if "results" not in geo_data or not geo_data["results"]:
        return f"❌ City '{city_name}' not found."

    location = geo_data["results"][0]
    latitude = location["latitude"]
    longitude = location["longitude"]

    weather_url = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast"
    weather_params = {
        "latitude": latitude,
        "longitude": longitude,
        "current_weather": True
    }
    weather_response = requests.get(weather_url, params=weather_params)
    weather_data = weather_response.json()

    if "current_weather" not in weather_data:
        return "❌ Weather data not available."

    current = weather_data["current_weather"]
    return {
        "City": location["name"],
        "Country": location.get("country", "Unknown"),
        "Temperature (°C)": current["temperature"],
        "Wind Speed (km/h)": current["windspeed"],
        "Time": current["time"]
    }

# 👇 this part runs the code
if __name__ == "__main__":
    city = input("🌆 Enter a city name: ")
    weather = get_current_weather(city)
    print("🌦️ Weather info:", weather)

  1. Save the file.

Now Run it the Right Way:

In PowerShell, type:

powershell
python weather.py

You said:
Using JavaScript and the Fetch API, write a function for beginner developers that takes a city name as input, retrieves latitude and longitude from the Open-Meteo Geocoding API, and then fetches the current weather data. The function should return a JSON object containing the city name, temperature in Celsius, and weather description. Include error handling for invalid city names, API failures, and network issues
ChatGPT said:

Absolutely! Here's a simple, beginner-friendly JavaScript function using the Fetch API that does exactly what you described:

✅ Features:

  • Takes city name as input

  • Gets latitude & longitude from Open-Meteo's Geocoding API

  • Gets current weather from Open-Meteo's Weather API

  • Returns a JSON object with city, temperature, and description

  • Includes error handling for:

    • Invalid city name

    • API failures

    • Network issues

📦 Full Working Code (beginner friendly)

javascript
async function getWeatherByCity(city) {
  try {
    // Step 1: Get latitude and longitude from city name
    const geoResponse = await fetch(`https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search?name=${encodeURIComponent(city)}&count=1`);

    if (!geoResponse.ok) {
      throw new Error("Failed to fetch geolocation data.");
    }

    const geoData = await geoResponse.json();

    if (!geoData.results || geoData.results.length === 0) {
      throw new Error("City not found. Please check the city name.");
    }

    const { latitude, longitude, name: cityName } = geoData.results[0];

    // Step 2: Fetch current weather data
    const weatherResponse = await fetch(`https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=${latitude}&longitude=${longitude}&current_weather=true`);

    if (!weatherResponse.ok) {
      throw new Error("Failed to fetch weather data.");
    }

    const weatherData = await weatherResponse.json();

    if (!weatherData.current_weather) {
      throw new Error("Weather data unavailable for this location.");
    }

    const temperature = weatherData.current_weather.temperature;
    const weatherDescription = `Weather code: ${weatherData.current_weather.weathercode}`;

    // Step 3: Return weather information
    return {
      city: cityName,
      temperatureC: temperature,
      description: weatherDescription
    };

  } catch (error) {
    return { error: error.message };
  }
}

🧪 How to use it:

javascript
getWeatherByCity("London").then(result => {
  console.log(result);
});

🧠 Example output:

json
{
  "city": "London",
  "temperatureC": 18.3,
  "description": "Weather code: 3"
}

📌 Notes:

  • Open-Meteo returns a weather code instead of text (like "Cloudy"). You can map this to descriptions if needed. I can help with that too.

  • No API key is needed — great for practice!

javascript
async function getWeatherByCity(city) {
  try {
    const geoResponse = await fetch(`https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search?name=${encodeURIComponent(city)}&count=1`);
    if (!geoResponse.ok) {
      throw new Error("Failed to fetch geolocation data.");
    }

    const geoData = await geoResponse.json();
    if (!geoData.results || geoData.results.length === 0) {
      throw new Error("City not found. Please check the city name.");
    }

    const { latitude, longitude, name: cityName } = geoData.results[0];

    const weatherResponse = await fetch(`https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=${latitude}&longitude=${longitude}&current_weather=true`);
    if (!weatherResponse.ok) {
      throw new Error("Failed to fetch weather data.");
    }

    const weatherData = await weatherResponse.json();
    if (!weatherData.current_weather) {
      throw new Error("Weather data unavailable for this location.");
    }

    const temperature = weatherData.current_weather.temperature;
    const weatherDescription = `Weather code: ${weatherData.current_weather.weathercode}`;

    console.log({
      city: cityName,
      temperatureC: temperature,
      description: weatherDescription
    });

  } catch (error) {
    console.error("❌ Error:", error.message);
  }
}
